slidetranscripts.Text: Amy is an anatomy and physiology student who is learning the circulatory system.
This is her first experience with the terminology associated with this content and her professor has assigned a reading from her textbook about human circulation.

In the traditional model of instruction, Amy would have sat in a lecture with no interaction with the content, instructor, or her peers and then tried to learn the information alone outside of class through homework.
This can lead to tremendous frustration and some students stop doing their instructional work outside of class because they get stuck.

Instead, in this scenario, after Amy reads the assigned text, she logs into the Canvas site for the course, and accesses the interactive Articulate presentation her instructor has created to reinforce the essential concepts from the reading.

Amy answers the questions in the Articulate presentation and reviews the content she got wrong by repeating part of the presentation. Because the Articulate presentation is designed to give immediate, targeted feedback, Amy can clear up any misconceptions during that review.
If she has any additional questions, she can submit those questions to the class discussion board on the Canvas course site.
The next day, Amys teacher quickly reviews all the questions that Amy and the others have posted in the Canvas discussion board.

He then begins their face-to-face class session by answering the questions posed by his students. By viewing the lecture or doing the reading or other preparation the night before the face-to-face class, the students can ask more significant, thoughtful questions. They benefit from the instructors presence in demystifying and clarifying any muddy concepts.
After these initial questions, the instructor passes the students images of the human body and asks them to map the circulatory system, as they had learned from the previous nights lesson.

He then provides them with scenarios that may impact the circulatory system. Students are asked to identify which functions of the system would be impacted in the case study provided and to explain why they would be impacted, using the terminology introduced previously. Because they are doing this exercise in class they can use each other, the instructor, and the content as a resource.

The students support each others learning as they work through the scenarios. The teacher moves through the classroom and engages the students to find out their response to the scenario and to provide feedback and direction to their approach to the problem posed.

This image represents what is recognized as the traditional model of instruction when compared to the flipped model shared in the previous scenario. You can see that each model shares similar elements and that it is only the order and the location of instructional activities that change. In a flipped classroom, the instructional content of the course, commonly delivered as a lecture, occurs outside of the classroom. Students engage with the content, their peers and the instructor during the face-to-face classroom experience.

Activities at home are in isolation but the class gets feedback when they are interacting with the teacher and the content.

Here are some characteristics of the flipped classroom. There is no single model for flipping the classroom but some of these common characteristics of this instructional approach would be considered part of the "flip.

This list represents some of the instructional approaches you may use to introduce and reinforce content using online/out of class tools. Each tool serves a different instructional approach but many of them can be used individually or combined to create a robust learning experience outside of the classroom.

Faculty at HCC have access to a variety of tools to create online instructional content for delivery outside of the classroom. Whether you want your students to view a recorded lecture, view flash cards or interact with a customized lesson, there are many options to support your goals - and their learning.

Learning for many of us is the result of shared experiences that incorporate action and reflection. The flipped model provides greater opportunities for students to interact in more meaningful ways with the content, their peers and their instructor. Students may bring questions about the content into the classroom, instead of developing misconceptions outside of class, in isolation. Faculty can require more from students in terms of making them responsible for their own learning.

Thanks for participating in this lesson.

Now that you have participated in the out of class portion of the flipped experience, jot down any questions you may have and bring them to the Flipped Classroom workshop or contact Instructional Media for further assistance. Think about whether you have any lessons that you would consider trying to flip and we can work on them together.
